00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:04.000
Let's say I have a linear
transformation T that's a

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:10.490
mapping between Rn and Rm.

00:00:10.490 --> 00:00:13.640
We know that we can represent
this linear transformation as

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:14.870
a matrix product.

00:00:14.870 --> 00:00:18.920
So we can say that T of x, so
the transformation T-- let me

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:21.360
write it a little higher to save
space-- so we can write

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:25.500
that the transformation T
applied to some vector x is

00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:30.440
equal to some matrix times x.

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:35.640
And this matrix, since it's a
mapping from Rn to Rm, this is

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:40.470
going to be a m by n matrix.

00:00:40.470 --> 00:00:43.270
Because each of these entries
are going have n components,

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:46.790
they're going to be members of
Rn, so this guy has to have n

00:00:46.790 --> 00:00:50.870
columns in order to be able
to have this matrix vector

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:52.910
product well defined.

00:00:52.910 --> 00:00:55.260
So we can go back to what we've
been talking about now.

00:00:55.260 --> 00:00:57.130
In the last couple of videos,
we've have been talking about

00:00:57.130 --> 00:01:00.130
invertibility of functions,
and we can just as easily

00:01:00.130 --> 00:01:01.850
apply it to this transformation,
because

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:04.190
transformations are
just functions.

00:01:04.190 --> 00:01:07.060
We just use the word
transformations when we start

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:11.120
talking about maps between the
vector spaces or between sets

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:13.220
of vectors, but they are
essentially the same thing.

00:01:13.220 --> 00:01:14.630
Everything we've done
the last two videos

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:15.530
have been very general.

00:01:15.530 --> 00:01:19.660
I never told you what the set
of our domain and the set of

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:21.540
our co-domains were
made up of.

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:24.240
Now we're dealing with vectors,
so we can apply the

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:25.640
same ideas.

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:32.220
So T is a mapping right
here from Rn to Rm.

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:34.830
 

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:40.470
So if you take some vector here,
x, T will map it to some

00:01:40.470 --> 00:01:42.870
other vector in Rm.

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:43.940
Call that Ax.

00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:46.550
If we take this matrix vector
product right there and this

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:49.450
is the mapping T right there.

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:51.840
So let's ask the same questions
about T that we've

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:54.000
been asking in general
about functions.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.250
Is T invertible?

00:01:55.250 --> 00:02:03.830
 

00:02:03.830 --> 00:02:06.390
And we learned in the last
video that there's two

00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:08.320
conditions for invertibility.

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:16.430
T has to be onto, or the other
way, the other word was

00:02:16.430 --> 00:02:17.680
surjective.

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.710
 

00:02:20.710 --> 00:02:22.720
That's one condition
for invertibility.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:24.950
And then T also has
to be 1 to 1.

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:31.340
 

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:38.390
And the fancy word for that was
injective, right there.

00:02:38.390 --> 00:02:40.850
So in this video, I'm going to
just focus on this first one.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:43.400
So I'm not going to prove to you
whether T is invertibile.

00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:46.820
We will at least be able to try
to figure out whether T is

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:49.480
onto, or whether it's
surjective.

00:02:49.480 --> 00:02:54.590
So just as a reminder, what does
onto or surjective mean?

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:57.840
It means that you take any
element in Rm, you take any

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:01.420
element in your co-domain, so
you give me any element in

00:03:01.420 --> 00:03:04.870
your co-domain-- let's call that
element b; it's going to

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:10.930
be a vector-- the fact, if T is
surjective or if T is onto,

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:14.710
that means that any b that you
pick in our co-domain, there's

00:03:14.710 --> 00:03:18.510
always going to be some vector,
at least one vector,

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:19.570
in our domain.

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:21.410
That if you apply the
transformation to it you're

00:03:21.410 --> 00:03:22.700
going to get b.

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:27.070
Or another way to think about
it is the image of our

00:03:27.070 --> 00:03:29.610
transformation is all of Rm.

00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:32.040
All of these guys
can be reached.

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:34.230
So let's think about
what that means.

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:36.820
So we know that the
transformation is Ax.

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:38.820
It's some matrix A.

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:41.410
So the transformation of x--
I'll just rewrite it-- is

00:03:41.410 --> 00:03:44.970
equal to some matrix A-- that's
an m by n matrix--

00:03:44.970 --> 00:03:48.660
times the vector x.

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:59.530
Now, if T has to be onto, that
means that Ax, this matrix

00:03:59.530 --> 00:04:06.680
vector product, has to be equal
to any member of our

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:10.140
co-domain can be reached by
multiplying our matrix A by

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:12.270
some member of our domain.

00:04:12.270 --> 00:04:13.760
So what's another way of
thinking about it?

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:19.920
Another way of thinking about
it is for any b, so onto,

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:27.930
implies that for any vector b
that is a member of Rm-- so

00:04:27.930 --> 00:04:40.372
any b here-- there exists at
least one solution to a times

00:04:40.372 --> 00:04:43.490
x is equal to b.

00:04:43.490 --> 00:04:52.600
Where, of course, x is, the
vector x is, a member of Rn.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:54.820
It's just another way of saying
exactly what I've been

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:56.540
saying in the first part
of this video.

00:04:56.540 --> 00:05:01.160
You give me any b in this set,
and then there has to be, if

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:06.130
we assume that T is onto, or for
T to be onto, there has to

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:09.570
be at least one solution
to Ax is equal to b.

00:05:09.570 --> 00:05:12.430
There has to be at least one x
out here, that if I multiply

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:14.720
it by A, I get to my b.

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:17.290
And this has to be true for
every, maybe I should write,

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:19.300
for every instead of any.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:20.170
But they are the same idea.

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:23.290
But, for every b in Rm, we have
to be able to find at

00:05:23.290 --> 00:05:25.900
least one x that makes
this true.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:26.890
So what does that mean?

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:37.680
That means that A times x has
to be equal to-- you can

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:45.670
construct any member of Rm by
taking a product of A and x,

00:05:45.670 --> 00:05:49.640
where x is a member of Rn,
where x is a member here.

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:50.520
Now what is this?

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:54.310
If x is an arbitrary member of
Rn, Let me write like this.

