00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:42.340
So here, maybe it might be
instructive to think about,

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:46.090
when can we not find solutions
to the equation

00:08:46.090 --> 00:08:49.960
Ax is equal to b?

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:52.710
So whenever you're faced
with this type of an

00:08:52.710 --> 00:08:54.270
equation, what do we do?

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:57.680
We can set up an augmented
matrix that looks like this,

00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:00.340
where you put A on this side,
and then you put the vector b

00:09:00.340 --> 00:09:02.770
on the right-hand side.

00:09:02.770 --> 00:09:05.340
And then you, essentially,
perform a bunch of row

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:05.870
operations.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:09.780
You have to perform the entire
rows in both cases, on both

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:11.800
sides, and we've done
this multiple times.

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:14.610
Your goal is to get the
left-hand side into reduced

00:09:14.610 --> 00:09:16.850
row echelon form.

00:09:16.850 --> 00:09:20.330
So what you want to do is,
eventually, get your augmented

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:22.240
matrix to look like this.

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:26.190
Where the left-handed side is--
let me define R, capital

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:30.460
R, to be the reduced row
echelon form of A.

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:31.820
And we've done many
videos on that.

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:36.160
That's just, you have a matrix
where you have your pivots and

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:40.680
the pivot will be the only
non-zero entry in its column.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:43.310
But not every column has
to have a pivot in it.

00:09:43.310 --> 00:09:48.140
Maybe, you have a free column
or non-pivot column and then

00:09:48.140 --> 00:09:49.570
they could have a
bunch of 0's.

00:09:49.570 --> 00:09:50.650
And maybe this has a pivot.

00:09:50.650 --> 00:09:53.000
This would have to be 0 if
there is a pivot there.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
These would have to be 0,
and so on and so forth.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.910
And maybe the next pivot
is right there.

00:09:57.910 --> 00:10:00.440
These would have to be 0,
and you get the idea.

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:03.230
You could have some columns
the don't have pivots, but

00:10:03.230 --> 00:10:05.880
whenever you do have a pivot,
they have to be the only

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:07.600
non-zero entry in
their column.

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:09.776
This is reduced row
echelon form.

00:10:09.776 --> 00:10:12.630
 

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:15.900
So, what we do with any matrix
is we keep performing those

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:18.100
row operations so that we
eventually get it into a

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:20.160
reduced row echelon form.

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:23.090
And as we do that we are
performing those same

00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:24.680
operations on the
right-hand side.

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:26.415
We're performing on
the entire row of

00:10:26.415 --> 00:10:28.340
these augmented matrices.

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:32.020
So this vector b right here, I
