If we don't have a solution for
some cases of b, then we

00:14:45.110 --> 00:14:52.180
don't span Rm.

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:54.840
I don't know if I'm overstating
something that is

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.600
maybe obvious to you, but I
really want to make sure you

00:14:56.600 --> 00:14:57.950
understand this.

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:01.680
Anytime you just want to solve
the equation Ax is equal to

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:04.350
b-- and remember, we want to
make sure that this can be

00:15:04.350 --> 00:15:07.440
true for any b we chose-- what
we could do is we just set up

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:09.510
this augmented matrix like this,
and we perform a bunch

00:15:09.510 --> 00:15:13.120
of row operations until we get
A, we get this matrix A to

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:14.770
reduced row echelon form.

00:15:14.770 --> 00:15:17.460
As we do this, the right-hand
side is going to be a bunch of

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:18.380
functions of b.

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:21.310
So maybe the first
row is b1 minus

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:23.600
b2, plus b4, or something.

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:24.850
And then the next row will
be something like that.

00:15:24.850 --> 00:15:29.770
We've seen examples of this in
the past. And if you end up by

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:33.670
doing the reduced row echelon
form with a row of 0's here,

00:15:33.670 --> 00:15:36.640
the only way that you're going
to have a solution is if your

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:41.080
vector b, if its entries satisfy
this function here on

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:43.800
the right, so that this
thing equals 0.

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:48.160
So it's only going to be
true for certain b's.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:51.680
And if this only has a solution
for the certain b's

00:15:51.680 --> 00:15:55.280
that make this equal to 0, then
we definitely are not

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:58.010
spanning all of Rm.

00:15:58.010 --> 00:16:00.660
Let me do it visually.

00:16:00.660 --> 00:16:06.030
So if that is Rm, and if we
put-- if this is only 0 for a

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:10.870
couple of b's, for, let's say
for some handful of b's, then

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:14.250
these are the only guys that we
can reach by multiplying A

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:17.030
times some vector in Rm.

00:16:17.030 --> 00:16:19.840
And we definitely won't
be spanning all of Rm.

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:22.650
In order to span all of Rm, when
we put this in a reduced

00:16:22.650 --> 00:16:25.550
row echelon form, we have to
always find a solution.

00:16:25.550 --> 00:16:28.180
And the only way we are always
going be finding a solution is

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:30.430
if we don't run into this
condition where we

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:31.780
have a row of 0's.

00:16:31.780 --> 00:16:33.460
Because when you have a row 0's,
then you have to put the

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:36.190
constraint that this right-hand
side has to be 0.

00:16:36.190 --> 00:16:39.070
So what's the only reduced row
echelon form where you don't

00:16:39.070 --> 00:16:41.020
have a row of 0's at the end?

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:44.560
Well, any row in reduced row
echelon form either has to

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:49.590
have all 0's or it has to have
a pivot entry in every row.

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:58.450
So the only way that you span--
so T is onto, if and

00:16:58.450 --> 00:17:06.170
only if, it's the column space
of its transformation vector

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:07.800
is equal to Rm.

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:10.859
Its column vectors
span all of Rm.

00:17:10.859 --> 00:17:13.930
And the only way that that's
happening is if the reduced

00:17:13.930 --> 00:17:33.970
row echelon form of A has a
pivot entry in every row.

00:17:33.970 --> 00:17:35.330
And how many rows
does it have?

00:17:35.330 --> 00:17:36.830
This is an m by n matrix.

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:40.730
It has m rows and n columns.

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:42.710
So it has a pivot entry
in every row.

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:52.500
That means that it has to have
m pivot entries, right there.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:54.640
Now, what's another way of
thinking about that?

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:58.240
Remember, earlier on, several
videos ago, we thought about

00:17:58.240 --> 00:18:01.270
how do you figure out-- and this
might confuse things a

00:18:01.270 --> 00:18:07.020
little bit-- how do you
figure out the basis

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:10.480
for your column space?

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:18.550
So the basis for the column
space of a matrix, and this is

00:18:18.550 --> 00:18:19.330
a bit of review.

00:18:19.330 --> 00:18:23.450
What we did is we say, look, you
take your matrix, and you

00:18:23.450 --> 00:18:30.980
put it in reduced row echelon
form of your matrix, and then,

00:18:30.980 --> 00:18:34.390
essentially-- let me draw it a
little bit different heree--

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:36.160
well, you put it in reduced
row echelon form.

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:38.360
So let's say that's just reduced
row echelon form.

00:18:38.360 --> 00:18:43.100
And you look at which columns
have pivot entries.

00:18:43.100 --> 00:18:46.360
And the corresponding columns in
your original matrices, in

00:18:46.360 --> 00:18:48.620
your original matrix,
forms the basis

00:18:48.620 --> 00:18:49.560
for your column space.

00:18:49.560 --> 00:18:51.640
So let me draw that out.

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:53.400
So, I'll do a particular
instance.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:58.240
So, let's say that it has its
column vectors a1, a2,

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:00.020
all the way to an.

00:19:00.020 --> 00:19:01.480
That's what A looks like.

00:19:01.480 --> 00:19:04.510
And when you put it in reduced
row echelon form, let's say

00:19:04.510 --> 00:19:09.370
that this column right here
has a pivot entry.

00:19:09.370 --> 00:19:10.370
That column has a pivot entry.

00:19:10.370 --> 00:19:11.420
Let's say that this
one doesn't.

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:13.110
Let's say this is a 2 there.

00:19:13.110 --> 00:19:15.030
I'm just picking particular
numbers.

00:19:15.030 --> 00:19:19.880
 

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:21.300
Let's say there's a 3.

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:23.990
Let's say all of these are
non-pivot entries, and then

00:19:23.990 --> 00:19:26.800
our last entry n is
a pivot entry.

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:30.180
So it just has a bunch of 0's,
and then a 1 like that.

00:19:30.180 --> 00:19:32.590
How do you determine what are
the basis vectors for the

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:33.800
column space?

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:36.000
Well, obviously, the column
space is everything that's

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:37.290
spanned by all these guys.

00:19:37.290 --> 00:19:38.840
But, what's the minimum
set you need to

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:40.280
have that same span?

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:42.610
Well, you look at which one
has a corresponding pivot

00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:44.230
entries or pivot columns.

00:19:44.230 --> 00:19:47.430
And you say, I have a pivot
column here, and I have a

00:19:47.430 --> 00:19:48.890
pivot column there.

00:19:48.890 --> 00:19:51.700
So the basis for my column space
must be this column in

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:55.240
my original matrix, and that
column in my original matrix.

00:19:55.240 --> 00:20:01.380
And then we said, well, how do
you define the dimension of

00:20:01.380 --> 00:20:02.220
it's column space?

00:20:02.220 --> 00:20:05.510
And you just essentially count
the number of vectors you need

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:10.340
for your basis, and we call
that the rank of A.

00:20:10.340 --> 00:20:11.180
This is all review.

00:20:11.180 --> 00:20:17.510
The rank of A was equal to the
dimension of the column space

00:20:17.510 --> 00:20:27.400
of A, which is equal to number
of basis vectors for the

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:29.140
column space.

00:20:29.140 --> 00:20:30.330
And this is how you
determine it.

00:20:30.330 --> 00:20:33.340
You essentially figure out how
many pivot columns you have,

00:20:33.340 --> 00:20:35.290
the number of pivot columns
you have is the number of

00:20:35.290 --> 00:20:37.510
basis vectors you have,
and so that's going to

00:20:37.510 --> 00:20:38.840
be the rank of A.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:40.870
Now, the whole reason why I
talked about this is we just

00:20:40.870 --> 00:20:49.070
said that our transformation T
is onto, if and only if, its

00:20:49.070 --> 00:20:52.850
column space is Rm, which is
the case if it has a pivot

00:20:52.850 --> 00:20:55.690
entry in every row in its
reduced row echelon form.

00:20:55.690 --> 00:21:01.490
Or, since it has m rows, it has
to have m pivot entries.

00:21:01.490 --> 00:21:05.100
So for every row, you have a
pivot entry, but every pivot

00:21:05.100 --> 00:21:08.050
entry corresponds to
a pivot column.

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:11.030
 

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:15.360
So if you have m pivot entries,
you also have m pivot

00:21:15.360 --> 00:21:20.960
columns, which means that if you
were to do this exercise

00:21:20.960 --> 00:21:25.240
right here, you would have m
basis vectors for your column

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:27.540
space, or that you would
have a rank of m.

00:21:27.540 --> 00:21:30.820
 

00:21:30.820 --> 00:21:33.780
So this whole video was
just a big long way of

00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:35.150
saying that T is onto.

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:39.976
 

00:21:39.976 --> 00:21:45.940
And another way of saying that
is that if you have your

00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:50.030
domain here, which was Rm, and
you have your co-domain here,

00:21:50.030 --> 00:21:56.930
that is Rm, that every member
of Rm can be reached by T by

00:21:56.930 --> 00:21:59.720
some member of Rn.

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:02.650
Any guy here, there's always at
least one guy here, that if

00:22:02.650 --> 00:22:04.400
you apply T to it, you
get right there.

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:05.800
There might be more than one.

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:07.560
We're not even talking
about 1 to 1 yet.

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:20.840
So we say that T is onto, if and
only if, the rank of its

00:22:20.840 --> 00:22:26.620
transformation matrix,
A, is equal to m.

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:31.140
So that was the big takeaway
of this video.

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:33.080
Let's just actually do an
example, because sometimes

00:22:33.080 --> 00:22:36.070
when you do things really
abstract it seems a little bit

00:22:36.070 --> 00:22:39.180
confusing, when you see
something particular.

00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:42.960
Let me define some
transformation S.

00:22:42.960 --> 00:22:48.870
Let's say the transformation S
is a mapping from R2 to R3.

00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:52.620
And let's say that S applied to
some vector x is equal to

00:22:52.620 --> 00:23:00.020
the matrix 1, 2, 3, 4, 5,
6, times the vector x.

00:23:00.020 --> 00:23:03.100
So this is clearly
a 3 by 2 matrix.

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:10.290
Let's see if S is onto.

00:23:10.290 --> 00:23:12.970
Well, based on what we just did,
we just have to go and

00:23:12.970 --> 00:23:14.870
put this guy in reduced
row echelon form.

00:23:14.870 --> 00:23:16.660
So let's do that.

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:20.150
So if you put this guy into
reduced row echelon form, so

00:23:20.150 --> 00:23:25.760
let's keep 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:23:25.760 --> 00:23:29.640
Now, let's keep the first row
the same, that's 1, 2.

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:33.470
Let's replace the second row
with the second row minus 3

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:34.540
times the first row.

00:23:34.540 --> 00:23:36.400
Actually, let's replace it with
3 times the first row

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:37.350
minus the second row.

00:23:37.350 --> 00:23:39.800
So, 3 times 1 minus 3 is 0.

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:44.900
3 times 2 minus 4, that's
6 minus 4, is 2.

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:48.780
Now let's replace the third
row with 5 times the first

00:23:48.780 --> 00:23:49.780
row, minus the third row.

00:23:49.780 --> 00:23:52.610
So 5 times 1 minus 5 is 0.

00:23:52.610 --> 00:23:56.850
5 times 2 is 10, minus 6 is 4.

00:23:56.850 --> 00:24:02.080
Now, let's see if we can
get a 1 right here.

00:24:02.080 --> 00:24:05.650
So I'm going to keep my
middle row the same.

00:24:05.650 --> 00:24:09.730
Or, actually, let's just divide
the middle row by 2, or

00:24:09.730 --> 00:24:11.923
multiply it by 1/2 So, you
get 0, 1 and then you

00:24:11.923 --> 00:24:14.910
have a 0, 4, 1, 2.

00:24:14.910 --> 00:24:18.170
And now let's try to make these
0, get it into reduced

00:24:18.170 --> 00:24:19.020
row echelon form.

00:24:19.020 --> 00:24:21.660
So I'm going to keep my middle
row the same, 0, 1.

00:24:21.660 --> 00:24:24.460
And let's replace the top row
with the top row minus 2 times

00:24:24.460 --> 00:24:25.250
the second row.

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:27.490
So 1 minus 2 times 0 is 1.

00:24:27.490 --> 00:24:30.170
2 minus 2, times 1 is 0.

00:24:30.170 --> 00:24:33.470
Now, let's replace this last row
with the last row minus 4

00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:35.500
times this row.

00:24:35.500 --> 00:24:38.080
So we get 0 minus 4,
times that, is 0.

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:44.560
4 minus 4, times 1, is 0.

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:49.840
So notice, we have a
row with 0's here.

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:58.940
We have two pivot entries or two
rows with pivot entries,

00:24:58.940 --> 00:25:04.460
and we also have two pivot
columns right there.

00:25:04.460 --> 00:25:14.390
So the rank of this guy right
here, of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:25:14.390 --> 00:25:18.290
The rank of that is equal
to 2, which is not

00:25:18.290 --> 00:25:20.090
equal to our co-domain.

00:25:20.090 --> 00:25:21.875
It is not equal to R3.

00:25:21.875 --> 00:25:33.180
It's not equal to R3, so S is
not onto, or not surjective.

00:25:33.180 --> 00:25:35.250
It's one of the two conditions
for invertibility.

00:25:35.250 --> 00:25:43.400
So, we definitely know that
S is not invertible.

00:25:43.400 --> 00:25:44.400
Hopefully that's helpful.

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:46.420
Now, in the next video we're
going to focus on the second

00:25:46.420 --> 00:25:50.830
condition for invertibility,
and that's being 1 to 1.

